	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-DR-19420615_01"/>
			<p>Just like the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/maps/wikipedia_52.5167_13.4.html">German Empire</placeName>, a number of special
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1033" type="subject">provisions</term> apply to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject">Ostland</term>. These Regulations are only to a very
				limited extent drawn up by the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1112" type="subject">administrative
					Authorities. </term> Thus, only a single related regulation is seen to have been issued by the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-485">Minister of State for the Occupied Eastern Territories</orgName>, see
				below under B.VIII, and the Office of the Commissioner of the Interior essentially confines himself to an Order of <date
					when="1941-10-13">13 October</date> of the previous year, regarding the Treatment of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-888" type="subject">Jewish Wealth</term> in the State Commission of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject">Ostland</term>. The Area Commissioners or the
					Self-<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-948" type="subject">Government</term> administrative
				Authorities have drafted the vast majority of provisions, and many of these Provisions are hardly published. As a result, the contents
				of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-542" type="subject">regulations</term> in question
				are more difficult to access for the legation, and there may also be some minor differences in the rules at the various locations. In
				the following, the legation will refer to some of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-337"
					type="subject">special provisions</term> applicable to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864"
					type="subject">Jews</term> of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject">Ostland</term>.
				Because of the foregoing, it is not certain that all the rules made <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-DR-19420615_02"/> under B. IV to VII apply
				throughout <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject">Ostland</term>. However, the envoy has
				intended to refrain from conducting an examination of the extent to which they are applicable everywhere, as their applicability in
				most places is undoubted, and it is probably more the general principles which have been adopted by the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1032" type="subject">authorities</term>. The following draws upon some of
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-337" type="subject">Special Provisions</term> of Interest.</p>
			<p>A. So far there is no <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject">provision</term> for what is
				meant by the term '<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jew</term>'.</p>
			<p>However, one would assume that the rules of this term in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181"
					type="subject">Ostland</term>, are similar to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-952"
					type="subject">ones</term> used in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159?dlid=deu" type="subject"
					>Germany</term>. […]</p>
			<pb n="3" facs="EHRI-DR-19420615_03"/>
			<p>B.I. The <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000254">Commissioner of State</persName> issued on <date
					when="1941-10-13">13 October</date> of the previous year a decree on Treatment of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-887" type="subject">Jewish assets</term> in the <ref
					target="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/admindistricts-74">Reich Commissariat Ostland</ref>, stating that all the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-888" type="subject">wealth</term> of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewich population</term> has been subject to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-585" type="subject">seizure</term>, commissarial administration and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-584?dlid=eng" type="subject">confiscation</term> in accordance with the
				provisions contained in the device. This includes <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-887" type="subject"
					>assets</term> of all kinds, such as real estate and movable property with all accessories and claims, rights and all kinds of
				interests.</p>
			<p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-333" type="subject">The right of confiscation</term> is the
				responsibility of the Commissioner of State or the authority, which he announces. It may include individual persons or the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> as a whole, and it may be restricted to
				individual <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-887" type="subject">property</term>. Excluded from the
				seizure is the part of the household deemed necessary for the personal life and cash, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-930" type="subject">bank</term> and savings deposits and securities at a
				total value of 100 Reichsmark. […]</p>
			<pb n="5" facs="EHRI-DR-19420615_05"/>
			<p>Even before the Completion of the administrative <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-951" type="subject"
					>order</term> of <date when="1941-10-13">13 October</date> of the previous year, There were within the various areas of which
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject">Ostland</term> consists, local regulations,
				which had been drawn up, imposing a registration requirement for all <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-887" type="subject">Jewish property</term> and prohibiting the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> from disposing of their property.</p>
			<pb n="6" facs="EHRI-DR-19420615_06"/>
			<p>II. In the cities, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewich population</term> lives
				in special <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">Jewish neighbourhoods</term>, separated
				from the rest of the city by high barricades. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-546" type="subject">Within
					the Ghetto</term>, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> are allowed
				to move freely, but they are prohibited from leaving the confined areas and could be sentenced to the death penalty if they do so and
				do not have special permission. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term>
				living in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghettos</term> belong to their own
				administration, choosing a kind of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-579" type="subject">Jewish
					Council</term>, which through its <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-554" type="subject"
					>chairman</term> is obliged to receive the orders of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-477"
					type="subject">authorities</term> concerning the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject"
					>Jews</term>. The Chairman is responsible for the execution of such orders. All the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> shall always obey the authorities’
				provisions, which he issues.</p>
			<p>III. All <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> are committed to wear a yellow
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">Star of David</term>, 8 to 10 cm in diameter on
				their chest - in for example <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/597427/republic-of-lithuania.html">Lithuania</placeName> also on
				their back.</p>
			<p>IV. All <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> that are able to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> must do so. They are employed through the
				Employment Office. For the work done by the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject"
					>Jews</term>, the employers must pay a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1050" type="subject">tariff
					wage</term>, but the labour profits are <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1048" type="subject">not
					paid directly</term>, but they are paid to the authorities. These then pay what the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> have earned for the work done to the
				Council mentioned under II, which in then settles with the individual.</p>
			<p>V. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> must not employ <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryan people</term> or give them shelter, a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1045" type="subject">provision</term> that has a special significance for
				Jews in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-944" type="subject">country area</term>.</p>
			<pb n="7" facs="EHRI-DR-19420615_07"/>
			<p>VI. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jews</term> are prohibited from using all
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-939" type="subject">public transport</term>. They are also <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-594" type="subject">prohibited</term> from staying in any public facility
				and park, visiting any <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1071" type="subject">public venue</term>,
				restaurant, places of amusement, museums, theatres and bathing places. In <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/597427/republic-of-lithuania.html">Lithuania</placeName>, they are not allowed to walk on the
				sidewalk, but are forced to use the right-hand side of the street thus two Jews are not allowed to walk beside each other but must
				follow one another.</p>
			<p>The special permits required for bicycling in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject"
					>Ostland</term> must not be issued to Jews.</p>
			<p>VII. For the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewish population</term>, special <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-834" type="subject">food cards</term> have been issued for which, in
				general, only <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">half</term> of the rations given to
				the rest of the native population are given. Generally, they have to make their purchases in certain designated stores. […]</p>
			<p>VIII. According to the Prime Minister's Decree of <date when="1941-12-19">19 December 1941</date> on the Establishment and Construction
				of a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1152" type="subject">German</term> Jurisdiction in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject">Occupied Eastern Areas</term> (§ 5), Jews do not have
				remedies against a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1152" type="subject">German</term> court decision.
				Nor can they petition for a resumption of a case or require a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1213"
					type="subject">judge</term> to vacate his seat on grounds of disobedience.</p>
			<p>According to one of the <ref target="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/admindistricts-86">Commissioner-General of the Reval</ref>
				issued on <date when="1942-03-03">March 3, 1942</date>, the Order for the Provisional Execution of Justice through the country's own
				judicial authorities (§ 4), all <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-899" type="subject">Jews</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewish</term>
				<q><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Mischlinge</term></q> or persons who are <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-582" type="subject">
					<pb n="8" facs="EHRI-DR-19420615_08"/> married to Jews</term> or in a straight line, excluded from any undertaking in the national
				administration of justice.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_dr_mohr_otto_carl">Otto Carl Mohr</persName></p>
